Module root that documents (in its doc comment) the complete mount layout the cage assembles — the authoritative reference for what's visible inside `bwrap` and why. Contains no logic itself; just re-exports from `build` and `config`.

Key invariant from the doc comment worth preserving when editing either submodule: `target_root` is bound RW at its *own host path*, not a fixed alias (ADR-046) — a build compiled inside the cage must produce paths identical to outside, so recovery is plain git rather than path remapping. `/etc/resolv.conf` is stubbed to an unroutable nameserver deliberately (ADR-049): omitting it makes the resolver fall back to `127.0.0.1:53`, which the empty network namespace refuses instantly and drives a retry loop that pins a CPU core. `/run/ctx` is the only egress path — it holds the API proxy socket, and the cage has no other network access.

Public surface: `build_bwrap_args` (in `build.rs`) turns a `BwrapConfig` into the final `Vec<OsString>` argv, pure/no I/O. `config.rs` owns `BwrapConfig` plus the fixed in-cage path constants (`CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RUN_DIR`, `CAGE_RESOLV_PATH`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, `API_SOCK_NAME`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CONFIG`, `CAGE_CLAUDE_CRED`, `CAGE_LOCAL_CLAUDE`) — any change to these constants must stay consistent with whatever the lifecycle module and the runtime cage-rules file (`/opt/cage/rules.md`) expect at those exact paths.